29
00:01:15,688 --> 00:01:17,690
UI can have on your game's overall branding.

30
00:01:18,470 --> 00:01:20,412
You will have learned a method of how to go about

31
00:01:20,432 --> 00:01:22,033
producing creative UI elements

32
00:01:22,194 --> 00:01:23,655
that complements your game's world.

33
00:01:24,315 --> 00:01:26,917
And last but not least, an understanding of the balancing

34
00:01:27,038 --> 00:01:30,200
act required between your narrative UI and usability.

35
00:01:32,448 --> 00:01:34,830
So with my history embedded in working with art direction

36
00:01:34,850 --> 00:01:37,651
and UI and UX for games, I learned a lot of what it means

37
00:01:37,711 --> 00:01:39,752
to work on games backed by great IP.

38
00:01:40,772 --> 00:01:43,153
And as I worked on these games, I grew to realize

39
00:01:43,193 --> 00:01:45,934
that one of the reasons why players play these games

40
00:01:46,174 --> 00:01:48,075
is not just because the game is fun itself,

41
00:01:48,816 --> 00:01:51,337
but it's because of the world these IPs stem from,

42
00:01:51,677 --> 00:01:53,418
that fans grow to love for years

43
00:01:53,658 --> 00:01:55,058
and sometimes even their entire life.

44
00:01:57,397 --> 00:02:00,260
And when I say worlds, I mean the fictitious universe

45
00:02:00,300 --> 00:02:02,583
created from mediums like film, games,

46
00:02:02,963 --> 00:02:04,785
and have their own individual culture,

47
00:02:04,985 --> 00:02:06,346
visual rules, and aesthetics.

48
00:02:07,407 --> 00:02:09,530
These worlds are the things people fall in love with

49
00:02:09,710 --> 00:02:11,311
because of the unique perspective they present

50
00:02:11,592 --> 00:02:12,813
that isn't of our world.

51
00:02:13,594 --> 00:02:14,835
And when it comes to games,

52
00:02:15,536 --> 00:02:16,397
and when it comes to games,

53
00:02:16,557 --> 00:02:18,339
the entire screen is an opportunity

54
00:02:18,419 --> 00:02:19,840
to help immerse a player in that world.

55
00:02:22,210 --> 00:02:24,912
So within a world, there are so many different visuals

56
00:02:25,092 --> 00:02:27,815
that one can take reference from when developing their game

57
00:02:27,835 --> 00:02:28,775
and their user interface.

58
00:02:29,796 --> 00:02:31,978
It's with the details that go beyond character art

59
00:02:32,138 --> 00:02:34,841
and environments like typography, iconography,

60
00:02:35,421 --> 00:02:37,483
color palettes that help keep a player immersed

61
00:02:37,743 --> 00:02:38,684
and engaged in a game.

62
00:02:39,565 --> 00:02:41,146
And in my years of working on interface,

63
00:02:41,767 --> 00:02:44,629
really what I've aimed for with Art Direction for UIUX

64
00:02:44,910 --> 00:02:46,291
is a branded experience.

65
00:02:48,197 --> 00:02:52,779
Creative worlds presented in games can make for a game's holistic brand vision and journey.

66
00:02:53,899 --> 00:02:56,580
And that's what you can achieve within a game's world and experience.

67
00:02:57,260 --> 00:03:01,881
A truly creative and exciting experience that through visuals, but also through functionality.

68
00:03:02,661 --> 00:03:08,963
While we often talk about user experience through via functionality, this player experience along with world immersion

69
00:03:09,463 --> 00:03:11,424
becomes defining of a great brand experience.

70
00:03:13,003 --> 00:03:16,566
Take for example Bioshock Infinite Game by Irrational Games.

71
00:03:17,066 --> 00:03:18,827
Yes, the game is a first-person shooter

72
00:03:19,087 --> 00:03:20,408
set in the early 1900s,

73
00:03:20,948 --> 00:03:22,609
but while you're not shooting up enemies

74
00:03:22,749 --> 00:03:24,750
or engaging in psychokinetic powers,

75
00:03:25,311 --> 00:03:27,492
you're still able to be immersed within the world

76
00:03:27,732 --> 00:03:30,474
while navigating crucial UI that enables the game

77
00:03:31,414 --> 00:03:33,375
to be played by the player in the first place.

78
00:03:35,815 --> 00:03:37,797
And that brings me to an important point.

79
00:03:38,297 --> 00:03:41,420
Just as important for a game to be visually immersive,

80
00:03:41,981 --> 00:03:44,783
games as interactive experiences need to be usable

81
00:03:44,883 --> 00:03:45,724
and easy to use.

82
00:03:46,404 --> 00:03:48,566
We want as little friction to happen

83
00:03:48,606 --> 00:03:50,388
so the player can enjoy the game's world

84
00:03:50,448 --> 00:03:52,209
because it plays into the bigger picture

85
00:03:52,369 --> 00:03:54,051
of defining a great brand experience.

86
00:03:54,812 --> 00:03:57,634
A pretty game is nothing with a bad user experience.

87
00:03:57,994 --> 00:04:00,416
So it's imperative that you focus on creating a UI

88
00:04:00,797 --> 00:04:03,379
that is simultaneously usable and immersive.

89
00:04:05,454 --> 00:04:07,535
Even with the Dead Space series by EA,

90
00:04:07,955 --> 00:04:10,516
the team successfully created a diegetic user interface

91
00:04:10,616 --> 00:04:12,376
that had yourself and the main character

92
00:04:12,836 --> 00:04:15,257
immersed in the same world and seeing the same UI.

93
00:04:16,017 --> 00:04:18,538
There is still, though, a simultaneous focus, however,

94
00:04:18,698 --> 00:04:20,758
on how everything is laid out and designed

95
00:04:21,259 --> 00:04:23,299
that enables the player to frictionlessly

96
00:04:23,499 --> 00:04:24,720
navigate the game's content.

97
00:04:26,499 --> 00:04:28,740
So when we talk about immersive elements with your game,

98
00:04:28,800 --> 00:04:30,921
which equals out to the entire user experience,

99
00:04:31,461 --> 00:04:34,422
UI has the same capability to immerse a player

100
00:04:34,462 --> 00:04:36,043
into a world just like characters,

101
00:04:36,543 --> 00:04:38,124
visual effects, and environments.

102
00:04:39,164 --> 00:04:41,685
UI is an opportunity to reflect your game's world

103
00:04:41,805 --> 00:04:43,586
and strengthen your game's visual branding

104
00:04:43,646 --> 00:04:46,927
through narrative, graphics, and of course, usability.

105
00:04:48,985 --> 00:04:52,288
So in a compact amount of time, I will discuss how to embed

106
00:04:52,328 --> 00:04:55,570
a game's world in its UI via these three phases,

107
00:04:56,070 --> 00:04:58,612
research, exploration, and iteration.

108
00:05:00,313 --> 00:05:02,875
So step one, let's create the foundation,

109
00:05:02,995 --> 00:05:04,816
power up and research your world.

110
00:05:05,457 --> 00:05:07,458
What is the world you are presenting to the player?

111
00:05:07,638 --> 00:05:09,860
What is the world influenced by culturally?

112
00:05:09,940 --> 00:05:12,542
What visuals, patterns, textures can you take on

113
00:05:12,582 --> 00:05:13,422
with your UI?

114
00:05:14,516 --> 00:05:16,618
This is a time to seek out the visual elements

115
00:05:16,658 --> 00:05:17,799
that make your world distinct.

116
00:05:18,480 --> 00:05:20,742
And it's quite possible that the same references

117
00:05:20,842 --> 00:05:22,443
your game's world is inspired by

118
00:05:22,523 --> 00:05:25,626
can be the same references that your UI can be inspired by.

119
00:05:26,267 --> 00:05:27,568
But there's so many different places

120
00:05:27,848 --> 00:05:30,070
your UI can get inspiration from.

121
00:05:31,472 --> 00:05:32,933
UI can be inspired by history,

122
00:05:33,473 --> 00:05:35,994
most notably how the Bethesda's Fallout series

123
00:05:36,134 --> 00:05:39,816
took inspiration from American 1950s post-war signage

124
00:05:39,916 --> 00:05:41,117
and technology interfaces.

125
00:05:41,817 --> 00:05:44,258
The Fallout series has a remarkably branded image

126
00:05:44,638 --> 00:05:45,399
through its UI.

127
00:05:45,579 --> 00:05:48,300
Typography, color, textures, all of it plays a part

128
00:05:48,400 --> 00:05:52,202
of keeping your universe immersed into the game.

129
00:05:53,383 --> 00:05:55,163
The UI evokes a powerful brand,

130
00:05:55,804 --> 00:05:57,565
while the player enacts with contact

131
00:05:57,625 --> 00:06:00,326
in a way that allows them a fun experience.

132
00:06:02,640 --> 00:06:04,402
UI can even be inspired by nature,

133
00:06:04,843 --> 00:06:06,345
as seen here in King's Paradise Bay.

134
00:06:07,105 --> 00:06:09,889
You can see how the button's color palette and treatment

135
00:06:09,969 --> 00:06:12,151
is reminiscent of oceans and natural rocks.

136
00:06:13,453 --> 00:06:16,256
UI can even be inspired by, say, a subculture,

137
00:06:16,936 --> 00:06:19,539
where it's very clear how games like Nintendo's Splatoon 2

138
00:06:19,619 --> 00:06:21,922
gets its inspiration from punk and urban references.

139
00:06:22,863 --> 00:06:25,144
While this universe is out of this world,

140
00:06:25,444 --> 00:06:27,625
their UI draws actually from very familiar,

141
00:06:27,685 --> 00:06:30,187
fun color palettes that you will see often in graffiti

142
00:06:30,327 --> 00:06:32,168
and other fashionable punk patterns.

143
00:06:33,108 --> 00:06:36,150
So big picture, UI doesn't have to just be

144
00:06:36,190 --> 00:06:38,091
a bright, juicy green button.

145
00:06:38,511 --> 00:06:40,052
There are plenty of ways to dress it up.

146
00:06:40,132 --> 00:06:42,873
So in a natural way that fits with your game's narrative

147
00:06:42,933 --> 00:06:43,573
if you desire it.

148
00:06:45,500 --> 00:06:48,181
Now all those games that I showed were already live,

149
00:06:48,501 --> 00:06:51,602
and for example of myself with this process,

150
00:06:52,122 --> 00:06:54,143
when I was working on Moana's Island Life,

151
00:06:54,883 --> 00:06:56,884
I had spent hours researching myself

152
00:06:56,964 --> 00:06:58,305
in the Oceania culture,

153
00:06:58,585 --> 00:07:00,886
which is what the movie itself is based off of.

154
00:07:01,606 --> 00:07:02,986
And when you are researching,

155
00:07:03,047 --> 00:07:06,408
you start to not only find keywords that define your world,

156
00:07:06,788 --> 00:07:09,009
but you start seeing inspiration for your UI.

157
00:07:10,131 --> 00:07:12,212
You start to see how icons can be designed,

158
00:07:12,252 --> 00:07:13,452
how silhouettes can be used,

159
00:07:13,952 --> 00:07:16,233
or what even kind of color palettes or typography

160
00:07:16,273 --> 00:07:18,653
you can dot to these three key words.

161
00:07:20,574 --> 00:07:22,514
And that is going to allow you to start researching

162
00:07:22,594 --> 00:07:24,875
handful of fonts that can complement your world,

163
00:07:25,715 --> 00:07:27,476
start developing a UI color palette

164
00:07:27,496 --> 00:07:28,936
that guides the user naturally

165
00:07:29,116 --> 00:07:31,137
while still maintaining a branded experience,

166
00:07:32,117 --> 00:07:33,377
or even provide inspiration

167
00:07:33,517 --> 00:07:35,638
of what kind of pop-up container shapes

168
00:07:36,058 --> 00:07:37,958
you can house your UI content in.

169
00:07:39,985 --> 00:07:41,905
So after researching your world,

170
00:07:42,245 --> 00:07:43,866
picking up visual cues and palettes,

171
00:07:44,066 --> 00:07:46,807
you can then take this all into exploration

172
00:07:46,847 --> 00:07:48,167
for a couple of sample screens.

173
00:07:48,907 --> 00:07:51,108
And by doing so, you can see what portions

174
00:07:51,128 --> 00:07:52,608
of your research is going to work

175
00:07:52,768 --> 00:07:54,209
and maybe not work so well.

176
00:07:54,949 --> 00:07:57,790
My suggestion would be to apply this exploration

177
00:07:57,850 --> 00:08:00,011
with something like perhaps a main game HUD,

178
00:08:00,171 --> 00:08:01,171
a character screen.

179
00:08:03,375 --> 00:08:06,157
So to recap, within research that acts as your foundation

180
00:08:06,197 --> 00:08:08,418
for your UI immersion, I would recommend

181
00:08:08,618 --> 00:08:10,980
looking into reference visuals and their details

182
00:08:11,020 --> 00:08:12,381
that inspire your game's world.

183
00:08:12,981 --> 00:08:14,842
If you can do that beyond Google by, say,

184
00:08:14,963 --> 00:08:18,745
watching movies, museum visits that

185
00:08:18,865 --> 00:08:21,627
are similar to the world that has inspired your game,

186
00:08:22,027 --> 00:08:23,388
that makes for even better reference.

187
00:08:24,469 --> 00:08:26,291
And finally, once you have all this research,

188
00:08:26,351 --> 00:08:29,655
you can then start taking it to the exploration phase.

189
00:08:30,336 --> 00:08:32,419
So then when we go into the exploration phase,

190
00:08:32,579 --> 00:08:35,103
this is our chance to build out our UI

191
00:08:35,203 --> 00:08:36,745
on perhaps a couple of key screens.

192
00:08:36,865 --> 00:08:38,748
And we want to answer the question of

193
00:08:39,068 --> 00:08:41,131
how do you immerse the world into your UI?

194
00:08:43,645 --> 00:08:46,809
And it's exciting, because all you have to do is just explore.

195
00:08:46,909 --> 00:08:48,531
I think this is a great opportunity

196
00:08:49,553 --> 00:08:52,476
to be able to explore all different kind of spectrums

197
00:08:52,537 --> 00:08:55,781
of visuals when you're setting out for your UI direction.

198
00:08:56,422 --> 00:08:59,886
To me, it's almost like, let's say, baking a cake.

199
00:09:01,145 --> 00:09:03,187
There's so many different ingredients to play with

200
00:09:03,528 --> 00:09:06,491
that not only influences the way that your cake tastes,

201
00:09:06,811 --> 00:09:07,752
but also how it looks.

202
00:09:08,433 --> 00:09:10,274
There's an endless amount of variations

203
00:09:10,334 --> 00:09:11,255
that you can proceed with,

204
00:09:11,456 --> 00:09:13,998
but this is a time with the range of UI elements

205
00:09:14,038 --> 00:09:15,720
for your game that you can think about

206
00:09:15,800 --> 00:09:17,221
how your player will enjoy the most.

207
00:09:17,842 --> 00:09:20,104
But what's important is that you explore the spectrum

208
00:09:20,284 --> 00:09:21,726
offered by your ingredients.

209
00:09:22,802 --> 00:09:25,605
These UI ingredients can allow for immersion,

210
00:09:26,045 --> 00:09:29,208
but within each one, there are different spectrums

211
00:09:29,428 --> 00:09:31,590
you can experiment with during your exploration.

212
00:09:31,970 --> 00:09:34,993
For example, diegetic UI or non-diegetic UI.

213
00:09:35,673 --> 00:09:37,155
Which one will work better for your game?

214
00:09:38,111 --> 00:09:41,236
And as a quick recap, diegetic UI is interface

215
00:09:41,256 --> 00:09:42,978
that is included in the game's world.

216
00:09:43,479 --> 00:09:46,203
For example, it can be seen and heard by the game characters.

217
00:09:46,843 --> 00:09:48,486
Non-diegetic, however, is interface

218
00:09:48,706 --> 00:09:50,669
that is rendered outside the game world,

219
00:09:51,049 --> 00:09:53,713
only visible and audible to the players in the real world.

220
00:09:55,478 --> 00:09:57,740
So with diegetic, you're able to gain

221
00:09:57,780 --> 00:10:00,281
a fully immersive narrative visually.

222
00:10:00,841 --> 00:10:03,502
It's great when the narrative is very natural,

223
00:10:03,602 --> 00:10:05,223
like let's say looking at a map

224
00:10:05,303 --> 00:10:07,824
the same way that Campo Santos Firewatch does,

225
00:10:08,284 --> 00:10:10,686
or even in Dead Space, because you and your character

226
00:10:10,806 --> 00:10:12,947
are in a spaceship, ultimately,

227
00:10:13,307 --> 00:10:15,128
you're looking at the same heads-up display.

228
00:10:16,328 --> 00:10:19,230
But there's also risk to diegetic UI.

229
00:10:20,778 --> 00:10:22,500
If you have a lot of information to show,

230
00:10:22,760 --> 00:10:24,382
there is a chance that crucial information

231
00:10:24,422 --> 00:10:27,925
can get buried due to the narrative UI.

232
00:10:28,145 --> 00:10:31,649
Complex tasks in the game may have a lot of friction

233
00:10:31,709 --> 00:10:34,111
due to a heavy cognitive load required by these tasks.

234
00:10:34,792 --> 00:10:36,493
And when you commit to a diegetic look,

235
00:10:36,713 --> 00:10:38,655
you're committing to preserving the fourth wall,

236
00:10:39,016 --> 00:10:40,617
which could prove later difficult,

237
00:10:40,817 --> 00:10:42,539
depending on your player's task in the game.

238
00:10:45,017 --> 00:10:47,879
And non-diegetic shouldn't be considered a loss of narrative,

239
00:10:48,239 --> 00:10:52,322
as it's there to help guide the player through complex tasks

240
00:10:52,422 --> 00:10:53,143
and strategies.

241
00:10:53,963 --> 00:10:56,525
And as you see with even games such as Riot's League

242
00:10:56,545 --> 00:10:58,646
of Legends or Atlas' Persona series,

243
00:10:59,107 --> 00:11:02,009
the two keep to non-diegetic because they

244
00:11:02,089 --> 00:11:04,110
have complex tasks and content that

245
00:11:04,170 --> 00:11:07,452
should be clearly separated so the player can easily

246
00:11:07,472 --> 00:11:07,913
play the game.

247
00:11:09,503 --> 00:11:11,584
But of course, the risk of non-diegetic

248
00:11:11,925 --> 00:11:14,967
is depending on how it is laid out and designed.

249
00:11:15,527 --> 00:11:17,769
Because the way, if it's badly laid out,

250
00:11:18,029 --> 00:11:21,731
you can risk further complicating your complex task.

251
00:11:22,212 --> 00:11:23,913
And if it's not designed correctly,

252
00:11:23,993 --> 00:11:26,895
then it will distract from the world being presented,

253
00:11:27,335 --> 00:11:29,236
in addition to just breaking the fourth wall.

254
00:11:30,337 --> 00:11:32,879
So, how do you explore the decision

255
00:11:32,979 --> 00:11:35,801
to have a UI that is more diegetic or non-diegetic?

256
00:11:36,742 --> 00:11:37,442
Well, it depends.

257
00:11:38,693 --> 00:11:39,754
Both can be narrative.

258
00:11:40,174 --> 00:11:42,156
This should be more of a decision based

259
00:11:42,196 --> 00:11:43,977
on your game's mediums and mechanics.

260
00:11:44,237 --> 00:11:46,038
For simple mechanics or console games,

261
00:11:46,538 --> 00:11:48,940
you may not need a non-diegetic UI

