00:25:34,952 --> 00:25:38,414
Hi, so you mentioned a few times about animated UI elements.

513
00:25:38,515 --> 00:25:41,377
I was just wondering if you had any specific methods or tools

514
00:25:41,397 --> 00:25:44,278
for kind of communicating the intended animation

515
00:25:44,319 --> 00:25:46,800
to developers or clients when you're kind of exploring?

516
00:25:47,160 --> 00:25:49,702
Right, yeah, I mean, it really depends on your resources

517
00:25:49,802 --> 00:25:50,383
at that point.

518
00:25:50,483 --> 00:25:52,224
Sometimes, depending on your games team,

519
00:25:52,244 --> 00:25:54,686
you have people who are naturally animators.

520
00:25:54,746 --> 00:25:57,247
Sometimes you have only resources,

521
00:25:57,347 --> 00:25:58,989
let's say, like PowerPoint, right?

522
00:25:59,709 --> 00:26:00,510
And I say that.

523
00:26:00,970 --> 00:26:03,552
from, it really depends on your comfort level.

524
00:26:04,033 --> 00:26:06,695
Sometimes even for myself, I will just use

525
00:26:06,755 --> 00:26:09,077
like a quick keynote, pending on the animation,

526
00:26:09,097 --> 00:26:11,399
just to demonstrate, okay, this UI element

527
00:26:11,459 --> 00:26:15,223
should move over here once I acquire this goal.

528
00:26:15,803 --> 00:26:18,145
So I would say it really depends on your resources.

529
00:26:18,165 --> 00:26:18,606
Yeah.

530
00:26:19,346 --> 00:26:19,667
Thanks.

531
00:26:25,292 --> 00:26:27,454
Do you recommend any

532
00:26:28,872 --> 00:26:34,401
practices or pieces of work that new UX designers should try and add to their

533
00:26:34,441 --> 00:26:37,105
portfolio if they're just trying to get into the industry?

534
00:26:38,307 --> 00:26:40,150
Right, I would say...

535
00:26:41,236 --> 00:26:46,861
That's an interesting question and I would say from that perspective, I think the best

536
00:26:46,881 --> 00:26:55,430
thing you can do as a UI designer starting out is just to create your own projects and

537
00:26:55,470 --> 00:26:58,833
to do so in a way that I think what's always a lovely demonstration.

538
00:26:59,634 --> 00:27:01,596
is when you show something like a game HUD

539
00:27:01,776 --> 00:27:03,418
and a character profile screen

540
00:27:03,499 --> 00:27:06,402
because that demonstrates your skill of layout,

541
00:27:06,582 --> 00:27:08,925
your skill of colors and typography,

542
00:27:08,945 --> 00:27:10,828
and you wanna be able to tell them

543
00:27:10,888 --> 00:27:13,631
that you can balance in between screens

544
00:27:13,671 --> 00:27:15,894
that have a lot of information that needs to be digested

545
00:27:15,934 --> 00:27:17,656
versus very minimal information.

546
00:27:17,676 --> 00:27:18,497
Thank you.

547
00:27:25,961 --> 00:27:27,983
So does localization ever play a factor?

548
00:27:28,003 --> 00:27:29,785
I know in my personal experience, I have artists

549
00:27:29,825 --> 00:27:32,207
pick great fonts that fit the world, and they don't have any

550
00:27:32,267 --> 00:27:34,349
European characters, so we can't localize.

551
00:27:35,030 --> 00:27:36,851
And maybe on the flip side, you need to do something like

552
00:27:36,891 --> 00:27:40,675
an IKEA manual that there's no text at all, but that might

553
00:27:40,715 --> 00:27:41,196
fit the world.

554
00:27:42,307 --> 00:27:43,188
That's a really good question.

555
00:27:43,248 --> 00:27:44,789
So in terms of localization,

556
00:27:44,849 --> 00:27:46,731
I think from an exploration perspective,

557
00:27:46,851 --> 00:27:49,914
you should be, when you're creating these UI screens,

558
00:27:50,155 --> 00:27:51,656
it should be very inspirational.

559
00:27:51,836 --> 00:27:53,258
And so from that perspective,

560
00:27:53,278 --> 00:27:57,902
you should try and find fonts that feel true to your brand.

561
00:27:58,002 --> 00:27:59,724
But then, and then afterwards,

562
00:27:59,944 --> 00:28:03,268
you can take that as kind of your goal

563
00:28:03,588 --> 00:28:05,530
and then look at fonts that are.

564
00:28:06,951 --> 00:28:09,854
that are able to be like localized for your game.

565
00:28:09,914 --> 00:28:13,497
And so I would say for your research and exploration part,

566
00:28:13,837 --> 00:28:16,579
you just look at what you feel like is the best font.

567
00:28:16,660 --> 00:28:20,002
And then after that, you go into localization fonts

568
00:28:20,022 --> 00:28:23,345
and then work with your font vendor

569
00:28:23,505 --> 00:28:25,587
to see which font will match closest to it.

570
00:28:30,448 --> 00:28:36,432
Do you have any, like, ideas or guidelines or recommendations for, say, user interfaces

571
00:28:36,472 --> 00:28:41,917
and user experience in games or immersive environments where there isn't necessarily

572
00:28:41,937 --> 00:28:42,677
a fourth wall?

573
00:28:43,340 --> 00:28:47,244
where instead of playing a character, you are more or less the character in something

574
00:28:47,264 --> 00:28:51,849
that is either slightly augmented reality or an alternate reality that is still making

575
00:28:51,949 --> 00:28:53,090
callbacks to the current reality.

576
00:28:53,110 --> 00:28:58,476
A lot of what I like to do is in those situations where there is a little bit of a blur between

577
00:28:58,956 --> 00:29:02,500
game reality and reality, so UX and UI there for me gets a little...

578
00:29:03,601 --> 00:29:10,127
confusing because I'm not quite sure what to do because there's not really a

579
00:29:10,167 --> 00:29:15,092
fourth wall and the only information presented to you is entirely separate

580
00:29:15,952 --> 00:29:18,735
and also the same as the character as you are the character

581
00:29:19,981 --> 00:29:25,582
Right, so in that respect, I would say that it depends on your game's nature, right?

582
00:29:25,622 --> 00:29:32,064
If it's a very story-driven game, then I think that you want to not necessarily, like UI is important,

583
00:29:32,084 --> 00:29:35,825
but then you want to make sure it's not distracting as well from the main experience.

584
00:29:35,845 --> 00:29:39,746
So especially if you're doing something like mixed reality, augmented reality,

585
00:29:39,886 --> 00:29:44,107
I would say that you want, if anything, you want user interface at that point to be very minimal.

586
00:29:45,167 --> 00:29:48,968
In terms of resources, I would say just being able to...

587
00:29:51,709 --> 00:29:57,231
Really being able to, I think, research about just like any other games that have been working on it,

588
00:29:57,251 --> 00:29:59,492
just seeing their findings as well would be a good idea.

589
00:29:59,512 --> 00:30:05,794
Because especially with AR, there's going to be new usability issues that

590
00:30:06,094 --> 00:30:09,915
you're going to be finding yourself. So it's a whole process, I think.

591
00:30:11,516 --> 00:30:11,756
Thank you.

592
00:30:15,744 --> 00:30:19,027
And I think actually we're out of time right now.

593
00:30:19,168 --> 00:30:23,052
And so I'll be just on the side if you have more questions.

594
00:30:23,232 --> 00:30:24,734
And thank you so much for listening.

